*Beyond Black-Scholes: Fitting Lévy Processes to Stock Returns*

**Week 1: Literature Review**

*Beyond Black-Scholes: Fitting Lévy Processes to Stock Returns*

MSc Statistics  ·  Applied Statistics Research Project

# **1. Introduction**

The dominant paradigm in quantitative finance since the early 1970s has been built on a deceptively elegant assumption: that the daily log-returns of a stock or index are independently and identically drawn from a normal (Gaussian) distribution. This assumption underlies the Black-Scholes option pricing framework (Black and Scholes, 1973) and powers much of classical financial econometrics. Yet a substantial and growing body of empirical evidence has documented persistent, systematic departures from normality in virtually every liquid equity market studied. Returns are leptokurtic — their distributions have heavier tails and sharper central peaks than the Gaussian predicts — and they are negatively skewed, meaning that large drawdowns occur more often than equivalent rallies.

This literature review examines the theoretical and empirical foundations for replacing the Gaussian baseline with the class of Lévy processes, with particular focus on two models that have received sustained attention in both academic research and practical risk management: the Variance-Gamma (VG) process (Madan, Carr and Chang, 1998) and the Normal Inverse Gaussian (NIG) process (Barndorff-Nielsen, 1997). The review also covers the empirical stylised facts that motivate this work (Cont, 2001), the Bayesian model evaluation framework used to compare fitted models (Vehtari, Gelman and Gabry, 2017), and the statistical backtesting methodology for Value at Risk forecasts (Christoffersen, 1998).

# **2. Empirical Failures of the Gaussian Model**

## **2.1 Stylised Facts of Financial Returns**

The most comprehensive and widely cited documentation of the empirical properties of asset returns is Cont (2001), which surveys daily return data across equities, foreign exchange, and commodity markets and identifies a set of robust statistical regularities — termed stylised facts — that appear with remarkable consistency across markets, instruments, and time periods.

The stylised facts most directly relevant to this project are:

- Excess kurtosis: the empirical kurtosis of daily log-returns is substantially greater than three (the Gaussian value), typically ranging from five to ten for major equity indices. Extreme moves — crashes and sharp rallies — occur far more frequently than a normal distribution would predict.

- Negative skewness: the distribution of equity returns is asymmetric, with the left tail heavier than the right. Large negative returns (losses) occur more frequently than equivalent positive returns (gains), reflecting the well-documented leverage effect.

- Semi-heavy tails: tail decay is slower than the exponential decay of the Gaussian but faster than the power-law decay of distributions such as the stable Paretian family. This intermediate behaviour motivates the specific class of Lévy models considered here.

- Absence of autocorrelation in raw returns, but persistent autocorrelation in absolute and squared returns — evidence of volatility clustering that is outside the scope of the present project but contextually important.

Cont (2001) emphasises that any satisfactory model of financial returns must replicate these properties by construction, not merely as a post-hoc approximation. This imposes concrete constraints on model choice and rules out distributions — such as the Gaussian and the Poisson — that either have too-thin tails or cannot accommodate skewness and the semi-heavy tail structure simultaneously.

## **2.2 Evidence from Major Stress Episodes**

The inadequacy of the Gaussian assumption is not merely a statistical abstraction. The S&P 500 data used in this project spans four major stress episodes — the dot-com crash (2000–2002), the Global Financial Crisis (2007–2009), the COVID shock (March 2020), and the Federal Reserve rate-hike cycle (2022–2023) — each of which produced daily return realisations that lie many standard deviations beyond what the fitted Gaussian would assign any non-negligible probability. The March 2020 crash, for instance, produced multiple daily moves exceeding five historical standard deviations within a single month. Under a Gaussian model, each such event is a near-impossibility; under a well-calibrated Lévy model, they are improbable but not negligible.

# **3. Lévy Processes: Theoretical Framework**

## **3.1 Definition and the Lévy–Khintchine Theorem**

A Lévy process is a continuous-time stochastic process with three defining properties: independent increments (the increment X(t) − X(s) is independent of the history up to time s), stationary increments (the distribution of X(t+h) − X(t) depends only on h, not on t), and càdlàg sample paths (right-continuous with left limits). Standard Brownian motion is the most familiar Lévy process, but the class is considerably richer.

The fundamental characterisation is provided by the Lévy–Khintchine theorem, which establishes that the characteristic function of any infinitely divisible distribution — and therefore of any Lévy process — has a specific canonical form determined by three components: a drift parameter b, a Gaussian variance σ², and a Lévy measure ν defined on ℝ\{0}. The Lévy measure controls the intensity and size distribution of jumps: if ν is the zero measure, the process reduces to Brownian motion with drift; if ν is non-trivial, the process exhibits jumps whose frequency and magnitude are governed by ν. The financial intuition is direct: jumps correspond to the sudden, discontinuous price movements observed during market shocks — events that continuous-path Brownian motion can never produce.

## **3.2 Subordination: Building Lévy Models from Brownian Motion**

Both the VG and NIG models are constructed via the technique of stochastic time change, or subordination. The idea is to evaluate Brownian motion not at calendar time t but at a random time T(t) that itself follows a Lévy process with non-decreasing paths (a subordinator). The resulting process inherits the independent and stationary increment properties of both the Brownian motion and the subordinator, and is therefore a Lévy process. The subordinator acts as a stochastic clock: periods of high volatility correspond to a rapidly advancing clock, periods of calm to a slowly advancing one.

This construction has an important practical advantage: it allows the parameters of the subordinator to be identified with economically meaningful quantities such as the rate and variability of information arrival in the market, following the trading time hypothesis of Clark (1973). More concretely, it provides closed-form or near-closed-form characteristic functions and probability density functions that are amenable to maximum likelihood estimation, which is a prerequisite for the frequentist component of this project.

# **4. The Variance-Gamma Model**

## **4.1 Construction and Parameters**

The Variance-Gamma process was introduced by Madan and Seneta (1990) and given its definitive treatment — including the option pricing application that established it in mainstream quantitative finance — by **Madan, Carr and Chang (1998) *** **"**The Variance Gamma Process and Option Pricing.**"* The model subordinates Brownian motion with drift to a Gamma process. Specifically, if W(t) is standard Brownian motion, θ is a drift parameter, σ is a volatility parameter, and G(t; 1, ν) is a Gamma process with unit mean rate and variance rate ν, then the VG process is defined as:

X(t; σ, ν, θ) = θ G(t; 1, ν) + σ W(G(t; 1, ν)).

The four-parameter family (µ, σ, ν, θ) — where µ is a location shift for the log-return — provides direct control over the four moments of the distribution. The parameter σ governs overall volatility; θ controls skewness (θ < 0 produces the negative skew observed empirically in equities); and ν controls excess kurtosis, with larger values producing heavier tails. A key theoretical property is that all moments of the VG distribution are finite, which distinguishes it from the stable Paretian family and makes it compatible with standard risk measures such as VaR and Expected Shortfall.

## **4.2 Probability Density Function and Estimation**

The probability density function of the VG distribution involves a modified Bessel function of the second kind, K_ν, which requires numerical evaluation but is available in standard scientific computing libraries. Maximum likelihood estimation over a sample of n log-returns is therefore feasible using gradient-based optimisation methods (L-BFGS-B), with standard errors recovered from the inverse Hessian of the log-likelihood at the optimum — a standard application of the Fisher information matrix approach.

Madan, Carr and Chang (1998) demonstrated that the VG model fits the implied volatility smile in options markets substantially better than the Black-Scholes model, providing both a theoretical motivation and an empirical validation for the model in a context closely related to the return distribution fitting pursued in this project.

# **5. The Normal Inverse Gaussian Model**

## **5.1 Construction and Parameters**

**Barndorff-Nielsen (1997) *** **"**Processes of Normal Inverse Gaussian Type**"* introduced the NIG distribution and its associated Lévy process as a member of the Generalised Hyperbolic family. The NIG process is constructed by subordinating Brownian motion to an Inverse Gaussian process — the first passage time of a Brownian motion to a fixed level — rather than to a Gamma process as in the VG case. The resulting distribution is parameterised by four quantities (α, β, µ, δ): α controls the overall shape and steepness of the tails; β governs asymmetry (β < 0 for negative skew); µ is a location parameter; and δ is a scale parameter.

The NIG distribution belongs to the class of semi-heavy tailed distributions: the tails decay exponentially — faster than power-law, slower than Gaussian — which is precisely the empirical behaviour documented by Cont (2001) for equity returns. Barndorff-Nielsen (1997) showed that the NIG distribution provides excellent fits to high-frequency financial return data, including foreign exchange rates, and that the process is closed under convolution, meaning that the distribution of the sum of independent NIG increments is again NIG — a property that is essential for the self-consistency of the model at different time scales.

## **5.2 Comparison with VG**

While both VG and NIG are four-parameter Lévy models that generalise Brownian motion to accommodate skewness and heavy tails, they differ in their tail behaviour. The NIG distribution has exponential tails that are somewhat heavier than those of the VG distribution for equivalent parameter choices, making it potentially better suited to capturing extreme events. The VG distribution, by contrast, has slightly lighter semi-heavy tails but retains finite moments of all orders. Whether VG or NIG provides a superior fit to S&P 500 returns is an empirical question that the AIC/BIC comparison and Kolmogorov-Smirnov goodness-of-fit tests in this project are designed to address.

# **6. Model Comparison and Bayesian Model Evaluation**

## **6.1 Information Criteria**

The classical frequentist approach to comparing non-nested models fitted by maximum likelihood uses information criteria that balance goodness of fit against model complexity. The Akaike Information Criterion (AIC = 2k − 2ℓ) and Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC = k log n − 2ℓ), where k is the number of parameters and ℓ is the maximised log-likelihood, both penalise models for additional parameters. BIC applies a stronger penalty that grows with sample size, which is consequential given the approximately 6,000 observations in the 2000–2024 S&P 500 dataset. These criteria will be supplemented by formal goodness-of-fit tests (Kolmogorov-Smirnov and Anderson-Darling) and QQ plot diagnostics that give particular weight to tail behaviour.

## **6.2 Bayesian Model Evaluation: LOO-CV and WAIC**

**Vehtari, Gelman and Gabry (2017) *** **"**Practical Bayesian model evaluation using leave-one-out cross-validation and WAIC**"* provide the methodological foundation for the Bayesian extension of the project. The authors develop Pareto-smoothed importance sampling leave-one-out cross-validation (PSIS-LOO) as a computationally efficient and numerically stable approximation to exact LOO cross-validation, which would otherwise require refitting the model n times. The key insight is that the LOO predictive density can be estimated from a single MCMC run using importance sampling weights derived from the posterior, with Pareto smoothing applied to stabilise the estimates when the importance weights are large.

PSIS-LOO and the widely applicable information criterion (WAIC) — also discussed by Vehtari, Gelman and Gabry (2017) — provide model comparison metrics that are directly interpretable as estimates of out-of-sample predictive accuracy, and that are applicable in settings where BIC's asymptotic assumptions may not hold. In the context of this project, comparing the LOO predictive accuracy of the Bayesian VG model against the Gaussian baseline will provide a coherent, decision-theoretic answer to the core research question: does a more flexible Lévy model offer a statistically meaningful improvement in predictive performance?

# **7. Risk Estimation and VaR Backtesting**

## **7.1 Value at Risk and Expected Shortfall**

Value at Risk (VaR) at confidence level α is defined as the negative of the α-quantile of the return distribution: it is the loss that will not be exceeded on a fraction (1 − α) of trading days. Expected Shortfall (ES) — also called Conditional VaR or CVaR — is the expected loss conditional on the loss exceeding VaR, and is a coherent risk measure in the sense of Artzner et al. (1999). Under the Basel III/IV regulatory framework, ES at 97.5% has replaced VaR as the primary capital adequacy metric for market risk, making the accurate estimation of ES a question of direct regulatory and economic importance.

For the Gaussian model, both VaR and ES are available in closed form. For VG and NIG models, they require numerical integration over the fitted density, or simulation from the model — both tractable given the closed-form PDFs available for these distributions. A key result this project aims to quantify is the magnitude of the underestimation of tail risk by the Gaussian model relative to the Lévy alternatives, measured in basis points of daily loss at the 99th percentile.

## **7.2 Backtesting: Kupiec and Christoffersen Tests**

**Christoffersen (1998) *** **"**Evaluating Interval Forecasts**"* develops the statistical framework for formally testing whether a sequence of VaR forecasts is well-calibrated. The paper introduces two key tests. The unconditional coverage (UC) test — which is equivalent to the Kupiec (1995) likelihood ratio test — assesses whether the empirical exceedance rate equals the nominal rate α. The conditional coverage (CC) test additionally checks that exceedances are serially independent: a model that produces clustered violations (multiple consecutive exceedances) is poorly specified even if it achieves the correct average rate, because it implies that risk is systematically underestimated during stress periods.

For the rolling backtest component of this project, a 500-day estimation window is rolled forward over the 2000–2024 sample, computing one-day-ahead VaR at 99% under each model at each step. The Kupiec unconditional coverage test is then applied to the resulting violation sequences. The Christoffersen independence test provides an additional diagnostic that is particularly informative given the four crisis sub-periods in the dataset, during which clustered violations would be expected under a model that fails to capture regime-dependent tail risk.

# **8. Synthesis and Research Gaps**

The literature reviewed above establishes a clear and coherent motivation for this project. Cont (2001) documents the empirical phenomena that any adequate model of equity returns must capture. Madan, Carr and Chang (1998) and Barndorff-Nielsen (1997) provide theoretically grounded and empirically validated distributional models that meet those requirements. Christoffersen (1998) supplies the statistical machinery to evaluate the practical risk management consequences of model choice. And Vehtari, Gelman and Gabry (2017) provide the Bayesian model evaluation tools that extend the comparison into a fully probabilistic framework, with formal out-of-sample predictive accuracy as the criterion.

What this project contributes beyond replicating these foundational results is a systematic, unified comparison across all four models — Gaussian, Student-t, VG, and NIG — applied to a single, long dataset (2000–2024) that encompasses an unusually rich set of tail events. The sub-period analysis, rolling backtest, and Bayesian posterior predictive checks together provide a multi-dimensional assessment of model adequacy that goes beyond the goodness-of-fit statistics reported in the original papers.

